{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}} {{Use British English|date=July 2016}} {{Infobox scientist |name = Jane Hamilton Hall |image = Jane Hall.jpg |image_size = 220px |caption = |birth_date = 23 June 1915 |birth_place = [[Denver, Colorado]] |death_date = {{D-da|November 1981|June 1915}} |death_place = |citizenship = |nationality = |alma_mater = [[University of Chicago]] |work_institution = {{hlist|[[Metallurgical Laboratory]]|[[Hanford Engineer Works]]|[[Argonne National Laboratory]]|[[Los Alamos Laboratory]]}} |prizes = Atomic Energy Commission Citation |doctoral_students = |doctoral_advisor = | thesis_title = The temperature diffuse scattering of X-rays by potassium chloride and potassium bromide crystals | thesis_year = 1942 | thesis_url = http://journals.aps.org/pr/abstract/10.1103/PhysRev.61.158 |spouse = |children = }}
'''Jane Hamilton Hall''' (23 June 1915–November 1981) was an American physicist. During [[World War II]] she worked on the [[Manhattan Project]]. After the war she remained at the [[Los Alamos National Laboratory]], where she oversaw the construction and start up of the [[Clementine (nuclear reactor)|Clementine nuclear reactor]]. She became assistant director of the laboratory in 1958. She was secretary of the General Advisory Committee of the [[United States Atomic Energy Commission|Atomic Energy Commission]] from 1956 until 1959, and was a member of the committee from 1966 to 1972.
==Biography== Jane Hamilton was born in [[Denver]], Colorado, on 23 June 1915.<ref name="AMWS">{{cite journal |journal=American Men and Women of Science |edition=12th |volume = 3, H-K |title=The Physical and Biological Sciences |location = New York / London |publisher=Jacques Cattell Press / R. R. Bowker |year=1972 |page=2431 |issn=0192-8570 }} Howes & Herzenberg give her birth year as 1923; this is an error.</ref> She entered the [[University of Chicago]], where she earned her [[Bachelor of Science]] (B.S.) degree in 1937, her [[Master of Science]] (M.S.) in 1938, and her doctorate (Ph.D.) in physics in 1942,{{sfn|Howes|Herzenberg|1999|pp=43–45}} writing her thesis on "the temperature diffuse scattering of X-rays by potassium chloride and potassium bromide crystals".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://catalog.lib.uchicago.edu/vufind/Record/4279528 |title=The temperature diffuse scattering of X-rays by potassium chloride and potassium bromide crystals |publisher=[[University of Chicago]] |accessdate=12 July 2016 }}</ref> There, she met and married David Hall, a fellow physics student,{{sfn|Howes|Herzenberg|1999|pp=43–45}} in 1939.<ref name="AMWS" /> They had two children, Malcolm and Linda.<ref name="Scientists Not Political Sages">{{cite news |title=Scientists Not Political Sages Says U.S. Woman Physicist |newspaper=Schenectady Gazette |date=13 November 1970 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1917&dat=19701113&id=T2hGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=A-kMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2872,3369801&hl=en |accessdate=12 July 2016 }}</ref> She was a member of [[Alpha Gamma Delta]], an international women's fraternity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/alphagammadelta/docs/winter_2018_q_issuu?e=1526429/58132839|title=Alpha Gamma Delta Quarterly|last=|first=|date=Winter 2018|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
After working for a year as instructors at the [[University of Denver]], they joined the [[Manhattan Project]], the effort during [[World War II]] to develop [[atomic bomb]]s, at its [[Metallurgical Laboratory]] at the University of Chicago.<ref name="The Atom">{{cite journal |journal=The Atom |volume=7 |issue=7 |date=July–August 1970 |title=Jane Hall to Receive AEC Citation |url=http://library.lanl.gov/cgi-bin/getfile?00847072.pdf |accessdate=12 July 2016 }}</ref> Nepotism rules prevented them both working in the same groups together, so while David worked on [[nuclear reactor]] design, Hall was assigned to [[Herbert Parker (scientist)|Herbert Parker]]'s Health Physics group, where she soon became head of its Special Studies section. Parker had her investigate the safety aspects of reactors, and she researched the hazards of inhaling [[plutonium]].{{sfn|Howes|Herzenberg|1999|pp=43–45}}
Hall was seconded to [[DuPont]], where she became a senior supervisor at the [[Hanford Engineer Works]].<ref name="The Atom" /> Hall and David moved there in mid-1944, and supervised the construction of the [[B Reactor]] there, followed by the D and F Reactors.<ref name="David Hall">{{cite web |url=http://manhattanprojectvoices.org/oral-histories/david-halls-interview |title=David Hall's Interview |publisher=Manhattan Project Voices |accessdate=12 July 2016 }}</ref> In October 1945, [[Enrico Fermi]] brought Hall to the [[Argonne National Laboratory]] as an associate physicist and assistant to himself as the laboratory director.{{sfn|Howes|Herzenberg|1999|pp=194–195}}
But in November 1945, Hall and David accepted positions at the [[Los Alamos Laboratory]].<ref name="David Hall" /> This was at a low point for the remote laboratory; with the war over most of the scientists working there wanted to return to their universities and laboratories, and were leaving in large numbers.<ref name="Scientists Not Political Sages" /> But the laboratory was working on cutting-edge science.<ref name="David Hall" /> They were given the task of supervising the construction and commissioning of the [[Clementine (nuclear reactor)|Clementine nuclear reactor]].<ref name="Clementine">{{cite journal|last=Bunker|first= Merle E. |title=Early Reactors From Fermi's Water Boiler to Novel Power Prototypes |journal=[[Los Alamos Science]] |date=Winter–Spring 1983 |pp=124–131 |publisher=Los Alamos National Laboratory |url=http://library.lanl.gov/cgi-bin/getfile?00416628.pdf |accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref> Clementine was the world's first [[fast reactor]], the first to be fueled by plutonium, and the first to use a liquid metal coolant,<ref name="The Atom" /> in this case, [[mercury (element)|mercury]].<ref name="Clementine" /> It went [[Criticality (status)|critical]] in 1946, and was used for scientific experiments until 1953, when it was dismantled.<ref name="The Atom" />
Hall's research interests included nuclear reactor development, [[X-ray crystallography]] and [[neutron]] physics, and [[cosmic rays]].{{sfn|Howes|Herzenberg|1999|pp=194–195}} In 1951 she informed [[Robert Oppenheimer]] of the results of the [[Operation Greenhouse]] George nuclear test, in which the yield of an atomic bomb was "boosted" by the addition of a small capsule containing less than {{convert|1|oz}} of [[deuterium]] and [[tritium]], which nonetheless increased the yield by {{convert|25|ktTNT}}.{{sfn|Rhodes|1995|p=474}}
Hall became assistant director of the Los Alamos National Laboratory in 1958. That year she was an American delegate at the [[Atoms for Peace]] Conference in [[Geneva]]. She was secretary of the General Advisory Committee (GAC) of the [[United States Atomic Energy Commission|Atomic Energy Commission]] (AEC) from 1956 until 1959, and was a member of the GAC from 1966 to 1972. When President [[Lyndon Johnson]] appointed her in 1966, she became the first woman to serve on the GAC. She was also a member of the AEC Advisory committee on Nuclear Materials and Safeguards from 1967 to 1972. She retired from the Los Alamos National Laboratory in 1970.<ref name="The Atom" />{{sfn|Sylves|1987|p=65}} In October of that year, the chairman of the AEC, [[Glenn Seaborg]], presented her with the Atomic Energy Commission Citation and gold medal.<ref name="The Atom" /> She died in November 1981.<ref name="David Hall" /><ref>{{cite url |title=United States Social Security Death Index," database |url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:JYN3-PZC |publisher=Family Search |date=19 May 2014 |accessdate=25 July 2016 }}</ref>
